From DeepL's English: Publishing and accessing scientific articles is very costly for research organisations. Is open access the perfect solution? Discover some real-life examples of publications that combine free access with high standards and rigour.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

"Thank you for participating in this survey on open access for long-form content. It should take about 10 minutes to complete.

&nbsp;
This is part of a study carried out by Information Power Ltd and commissioned by RLUK in partnership with SCONUL and ARMA as part of the Advancing Long-form Open Access Practice Project​. The survey sits alongside a series of focus groups covering various aspects of this topic. Your experience and insights will help us assess the practicality and priorities for key library strategies to promote long-form OA​​. Please note that we are seeking individual responses rather than a consolidated institutional response."

"Open Humanities is the newsletter of Open Humanities Press (OHP), a radical, scholar-led, open access publisher of critical and cultural theory that was initiated in 2006 and launched publicly in 2008. The newsletter features contributions from those associated with the Press, alongside others engaging with its ideas, publications and practices.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

The Open Humanities newsletter – which we hope to send out semi-regularly – explores what it means to create, publish and circulate knowledge in a moment marked by the erosion of liberal democracies and the unravelling of the neoliberal world order, coupled with the increasing marketisation of knowledge and education. In doing so, it questions many inherited assumptions: about authorship and creativity, copyright and ownership, politics and culture, class and inequality, even about the very idea of ‘the human’."

